nguage": "en-us,en;q=0.5", "Sec-Fetch-Mode": "navigate", "Referer": "https://www.instagram.com/"}, "video_ext": "mp4", "audio_ext": "none", "abr": 0, "vbr": 620.026, "format": "dash-1437551081343633v - 720x1280 (DASH video)"}], "title": "Video by crime.short", "description": "In 1836, a man named Leopold von Sacher-Masoch was born in the Austrian Empire.\nHe was not a criminal, nor a fictional character, but a real writer and thinker whose life would later influence psychology itself.\nMasoch grew up in a strict and authoritarian environment.\nFrom a young age, he was deeply affected by ideas of power, punishment, and obedience.\nRather than acting on these thoughts, he explored them through literature.\nIn 1870, he published his most famous novel, Venus in Furs.\nThe book was not written to glorify pain, but to examine the psychological conflict between control and submission.\nIt portrayed a man who willingly gives up power, believing that surrender gives his life meaning.\nYears later, European psychiatrists began classifying human behaviors scientifically.\nIn 1886, Austrian psychiatrist Richard von Krafft-Ebing introduced the term “Masochism” in his medical work, naming it after Sacher-Masoch.\nThis decision was not made with Masoch’s consent.\nWhen he discovered that his name had become a medical term, he was deeply upset and tried to stop it—but failed.\nLeopold von Sacher-Masoch died in 1895, poor and largely forgotten.\nYet his name lived on, permanently attached to a psychological concept he never intended to represent.\nMasochism was not born from myth or crime,\nbut from a real man, whose attempt to understand the human mind ended up defining it in an unexpected way.", "duration": 7.036, "timestamp": 1770028867, "uploader_id": "78363994764", "uploader": "CrimeShort", "channel": "crime.short", "like_count": 60224, "comment_count": 278, "comments": [{"author": "tai_atera", "author_id": "357095470", "id": "17951390210966061", "text": "Venus im Pelz ❤️", "ti